"is not fit to innovate. Upon the whole matter, a poet must first be certain that the word he would mtroduce is beautiful in the Latin, and is to consi- der, in the next place, whether it will agree with the English idiom ; after this, he ought to take the opinion of judicious friends, such as are learned in both languages : and lastly, since no man is infalli- bie, let bim use this licence very sparingly ; for, if too many forcign words are poured in upon us, it looks as if they were designed not to assist the na- tives, but to conquer them."